Anhydrite (CaSO4) is relatively insoluble in water. However, when it comes into contact with water, it can slowly transform into gypsum (CaSO4·2H2O), which is more soluble. This transformation process can create micro-cracks in the rock, allowing more water to penetrate and dissolve the gypsum.

Sulfuric acid plays a crucial role in this process. It can be produced by certain types of bacteria that oxidize hydrogen sulfide (H2S) gas, which can be found in oil deposits or hot springs often associated with gypsum formations. The sulfuric acid produced by these bacteria can react with the gypsum to form calcium sulfate, which is highly soluble, and carbon dioxide.

The chemical reaction is as follows:

H2SO4 (sulfuric acid) + CaSO4·2H2O (gypsum) -> CaSO4 (calcium sulfate) + 2H2O (water) + CO2 (carbon dioxide)

